Big O Notation in Java

Big O Notation is used to describe how fast an algorithm works
as the size of input data grows.

It shows how time or memory increases, not exact speed.

Simple Idea

Big O answers the question:

👉 “What happens when data becomes very large?”

Most Common Complexities
O(1) — Constant Time
int x = arr[0];
always same speed
does not depend on input size
O(n) — Linear Time
for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    System.out.println(arr[i]);
}
grows linearly
more data → more time
O(log n) — Logarithmic Time
// example: binary search
data is divided each step
very fast for large datasets
O(n²) — Quadratic Time
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
        System.out.println(i + " " + j);
    }
}
very slow for big data
often appears with nested loops
Visualization (Growth Speed)
O(1)   → best
O(log n)
O(n)
O(n log n)
O(n²) → bad
Why Big O is Important
helps compare algorithms
shows scalability
helps write efficient code
Real Examples in Java
ArrayList.get() → O(1)
ArrayList.contains() → O(n)
Binary Search → O(log n)
Nested loops → O(n²)
Key Rules (Simple)
ignore constants → O(2n) = O(n)
focus on biggest growth → O(n² + n) = O(n²)
loops → usually O(n)
nested loops → multiply → O(n²)
Summary
Big O measures efficiency
focuses on growth, not exact time
helps choose better algorithms
most important types:
O(1)
O(n)
O(log n)
O(n²)
